The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 The Indian Medical Association (IMA) on Thursday appealed to chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee to provide security to doctors in the city and the districts.

 he association organised a march from Nil Ratan Sircar Medical College and Hospital to Rani Rashmoni Avenue to protest the repeated incidents of assault on doctors. Apart from Jayanta Ghosh, the list of victims includes Susil Pal and Chandan Sen. IMA joint secretary (Bengal branch) Sanjoy Banerjee said the chief minister had sought a report on the attacks. 

 The two teenagers who died under mysterious circumstances at an eatery on Mirza Ghalib Street on Tuesday night could have suffered food poisoning and dehydration, police said on Thursday. Deputy commissioner of police (detective department) Gyanwant Singh said food samples have been sent to a forensic laboratory. However, relatives of Kausar Ali, 16, and Manawar Hussain, 18, claimed that the two were victims of a ?deep-rooted conspiracy?. 

 The Bangiya Christiya Pariseba on Thursday threatened to launch a ?fast-unto-death? if the government refused to withdraw the School Service Commission (Amendment) Bill, which makes it mandatory for state-aided Christian schools to recruit teachers through the school service commission. 

 Two persons were critically injured in separate accidents on the Lockgate Road flyover, under Chitpur police station, on Thursday morning. Apurva Das, 45, who is physically challenged, was knocked down by a Tata Sumo while he was riding his three-wheeler scooter. 

 n the second incident, a military truck hit a 29-year-old motorcyclist, Deepak Joshi. Police said the truck ignored a no-entry sign and was plying towards the north. Both victims have been admitted to RG Kar Medical College and Hospital.

 Chief metropolitan magistrate Jaladhar Mandal on Thursday remanded Dinesh Dalmia, a key accused in a Rs 110-crore scam involving stock exchanges in Delhi, Chennai and Calcutta, in police custody till March 24. The magistrate had earlier remanded Dalmia, who was brought to the city following his arrest at New Delhi airport, in judicial custody. Deputy commissioner (detective department) Gyanwant Singh said sleuths needed Dalmia in their custody for interrogation.

 Madhusudan Das, 50, was found dead in a private bus in Mahestala, on the city?s southern fringes, on Thursday morning. There were deep wounds on the back of his head. Police suspect Das, who used to supply building material, was murdered over a business rivalry. 

 Two alleged extortionists were arrested in Salt Lake by the special operation group of the CID on Thursday afternoon. An officer said Jivan, 25, and Ajay, 20, used to operate in North 24-Parganas. 

 Megha Vaid, 17, was seriously injured when her car rammed into another at the crossing of Park Street and Loudon Street on Thursday. Police said Megha suffered critical injuries in the head and was taken to Ramakrishna Mission Seva Pratisthan.

 Six persons were injured in a clash between two groups of CPM activists over possession of a plot in Bishnupur, on the city?s southern fringes, on Thursday. Police said both groups hurled bombs and fired at one another. The injured were admitted to a local hospital. Five persons have been detained.

 TO C.M.L.C. 65 for donating cakes, pulses, bananas, rice and oil to an orphanage for boys




